Wildfire Analysis in Protected Area of San Martín Region (2000–2024)

Bikal Shrestha

December 14, 2025

1 Introduction

This document presents a comprehensive analysis of wildfire patterns in the San Martín Region of Peru from 2001 to 2024, with a special focus on protected areas.

2 Load Required Packages

# Load required packages
library(sf)
library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyr)

3 Load Data

4 Study Area Overview

4.1 San Martín Department with Protected Areas

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = sanmartin_sf, 
          fill = "lightgreen", 
          color = "darkgreen", 
          alpha = 0.6,
          size = 1.2) +

  theme_bw() +

# Aggregate fire counts by year
yearly_stats <- all_fires %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%

7 Protected Areas Analysis

7.1 Fires: Protected vs Non-Protected Areas

# Calculate fires in protected vs non-protected areas
fires_comparison <- all_fires %>%
  mutate(in_protected = lengths(st_intersects(., protected_areas)) > 0) %>%
  group_by(year, in_protected) %>%
  summarise(fire_count = n(), .groups = 'drop')

# Plot temporal trends
ggplot(fires_comparison, aes(x = year, y = fire_count, color = in_protected)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("TRUE" = "red", "FALSE" = "blue"),
    labels = c("Outside Protected", "Inside Protected")

  theme_minimal() +

7.2 Fire Density Hotspots

# Create grid
grid <- st_make_grid(sanmartin_sf, cellsize = 0.1, square = FALSE) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(grid_id = row_number())

# Count fires per grid cell
fires_per_grid <- st_join(grid, all_fires) %>%
  group_by(grid_id) %>%
  summarise(fire_count = n(), .groups = 'drop')

# Map fire hotspots
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = sanmartin_sf, fill = "lightgray", color = "black") +
  geom_sf(data = fires_per_grid, aes(fill = fire_count), alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_sf(data = protected_areas, fill = NA, color = "red", size = 1) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "inferno") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Fire Density Hotspots in San Martín",
    fill = "Fire Count"
  ) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"))

8 Buffer Zone Analysis

8.1 Fire Distribution Relative to Protected Areas (Area Chart)

# Analyze fires near protected area boundaries
protected_buffer <- st_buffer(protected_areas, dist = 5000)  # 5km buffer

fires_near_protected <- all_fires %>%
  mutate(
    inside = lengths(st_intersects(., protected_areas)) > 0,
    in_buffer = lengths(st_intersects(., protected_buffer)) > 0 & !inside
  ) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    inside_count = sum(inside),
    buffer_count = sum(in_buffer, na.rm = TRUE),
    outside_count = sum(!inside & !in_buffer, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = 'drop'
  )

# Visualize buffer analysis
fires_near_protected_long <- fires_near_protected %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = ends_with("_count"), 
               names_to = "zone", 
               values_to = "count")

ggplot(fires_near_protected_long, aes(x = year, y = count, fill = zone)) +
  geom_area(alpha = 0.6) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("inside_count" = "darkred", 
               "buffer_count" = "orange", 
               "outside_count" = "lightblue"),
    labels = c("Inside Protected", "5km Buffer", "Outside")
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Fire Distribution Relative to Protected Areas",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Number of Fires",
    fill = "Zone"
  ) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"))

8.3 Spatial Distribution by Zone

# Classify each fire point by zone
fires_classified <- all_fires %>%
  mutate(
    inside = lengths(st_intersects(., protected_areas)) > 0,
    in_buffer = lengths(st_intersects(., protected_buffer)) > 0
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    zone = case_when(
      inside ~ "Inside Protected Area",
      in_buffer & !inside ~ "Buffer Zone (5km)",
      TRUE ~ "Outside"
    )
  )

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = sanmartin_sf, fill = "gray95", color = "gray50") +
  geom_sf(data = protected_buffer, fill = "orange", alpha = 0.2, color = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = protected_areas, fill = "darkgreen", alpha = 0.4, color = "darkgreen", size = 0.5) +
  geom_sf(data = fires_classified, aes(color = zone), size = 0.8, alpha = 0.6) +
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("Inside Protected Area" = "darkred", 
               "Buffer Zone (5km)" = "orange", 
               "Outside" = "steelblue")
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Wildfire Locations by Zone in San Martín",
    subtitle = "Protected Areas with 5km Buffer Zone",
    color = "Fire Location",
    caption = "Green = Protected Areas, Orange shading = 5km Buffer Zone"
  ) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold", size = 14),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 11),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray90")
  )

# Add time periods
fires_classified <- fires_classified %>%

      year >= 2017 & year <= 2024 ~ "2017-2024"
    )
  )

ggplot() +

# Select Cordillera Escalera protected area

10 Findings

This analysis reveals important patterns in wildfire occurrence in the San Martín region:

  1. Temporal trends: Fire detections show high interannual variability with notable peaks in 2010, 2014, and 2017, while the overall trend indicates a gradual increase from approximately 200 fires in 2001 to over 700 by 2024. This upward trajectory suggests growing fire pressure in the region, likely driven by land-use changes and climate factors.
  2. Seasonal patterns: Fire activity exhibits a distinct seasonal concentration during August, September, and October, corresponding to the dry season. This consistent pattern across all years indicates that fire occurrence is strongly controlled by seasonal climatic conditions rather than random events.
  3. Protected areas: Protected areas have been remarkably effective in preventing fires, with consistently low fire occurrence inside protected boundaries throughout the 24-year period. In contrast, fires outside protected areas show high variability and increasing trends, demonstrating that conservation management successfully mitigates fire risk.
  4. Buffer zones: The 5km buffer zones around protected areas experience moderate fire pressure, particularly along western and southern edges, indicating external threats to protected area boundaries. However, very few fires penetrate into core protected zones, suggesting that management practices effectively prevent fire spread from buffer zones into conservation areas.
  5. Spatial hotspots: Fire density analysis reveals a clear north-south corridor of high fire concentration through central San Martín, with the highest densities (200+ events per grid cell) occurring at 15-25 km from protected areas. Protected areas are strategically positioned away from these high-intensity fire zones, contributing to their effectiveness in fire prevention.

11 Overall Conclusion

This 24-year analysis demonstrates that while regional fire pressure is increasing in San Martín, protected areas remain highly effective fire prevention zones with minimal internal fire occurrence. The combination of seasonal predictability, spatial concentration patterns, and successful protected area management provides a strong foundation for developing targeted fire prevention strategies and landscape-level conservation approaches.
